=====Usage notes=====
* Many nouns formed with ''-ity'' are uncountable; those that are countable form their plurals in ''-ities''.
* The addition of ''-ity'' to an adjective results in a shift of stress to the antepenultimate syllable; that is, words in ''-ity'' are stressed on the last syllable before the ''-ity'', even in cases where this syllable is part of another suffix (as in words in ''[[-ability]]'' and ''[[-icity]]''). Further, this shift typically results in a change in vowel quality; compare, for example, ''[[real]]'' and ''[[reality]]'', where the sound {{IPAchar|[√¶]}} in the second word is not present in the first. These vowel quality changes are usually consistent with the spelling of both forms ‚Äî note that the letter &lt;a> in the second word ''is'' present in the first ‚Äî but sometimes spelling changes are seen, as with the suffix ''[[-ous]]'', which when it combines with ''-ity'' produces the suffix ''[[-osity]]''.
* While a final ''-c'' is pronounced {{IPAchar|[k]}}, before ''-ity'' it becomes {{IPAchar|[s]}}; compare, for example, ''[[elastic]]'' and ''[[elasticity]]''.
* Final ''-e'' is dropped before adding this suffix.

